CORDOVA ENERGY COMPANY LLC RATE SCHEDULE FERC NO. 1
Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service
Cordova Energy Company LLC ("Cordova") provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service ("Reactive Supply Service") from a natural gas-fueled, combined-cycle generation facility located in Rock Island County, Illinois within the Commonwealth Edison Company ("ComEd") Zone of the control area administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") in order to assist in maintaining transmission voltages within acceptable limits on the PJM transmission system. This Rate Schedule sets forth Cordova's revenue requirements for the provision of Reactive Supply Service, as contemplated by Schedule 2 of the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff, which provides that PJM will pay generation owners their monthly revenue requirement for Reactive Supply Service. This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. REVENUE REQUIREMENT: Total Revenue Requirement: Cordova's Total Annual Revenue Requirement shall be calculated as follows: Fixed Annual Revenue Requirement is: $1,032,150 Monthly Revenue Requirement is: $86,012 (based on Fixed Annual Revenue Requirement divided by 12)

CORDOVA ENERGY COMPANY LLC RATE SCHEDULE FERC NO. 1
Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service
Cordova Energy Company LLC ("Cordova") provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service ("Reactive Supply Service") from a natural gas-fueled, combined-cycle generation facility located in Rock Island County, Illinois within the Commonwealth Edison Company ("ComEd") Zone of the control area administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") in order to assist in maintaining transmission voltages within acceptable limits on the PJM transmission system. This Rate Schedule sets forth Cordova's revenue requirements for the provision of Reactive Supply Service, as contemplated by Schedule 2 of the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff, which provides that PJM will pay generation owners their monthly revenue requirement for Reactive Supply Service. This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. REVENUE REQUIREMENT: Total Revenue Requirement: Cordova's Total Annual Revenue Requirement shall be calculated as follows: Fixed Annual Revenue Requirement is: $850,000.08 Monthly Revenue Requirement is: $70,833.34 (based on Fixed Annual Revenue Requirement divided by 12)

CORDOVA ENERGY COMPANY LLC MARKET-BASED RATE TARIFF Section 1: Availability Cordova Energy Company (“Seller”) may sell energy and/or capacity from time to time at rates, terms and conditions established by agreement of the Parties. All such transactions shall be voluntary. Seller also may sell to purchasers the ancillary services listed in this Section 1: a. RTO/ISO Specific PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (“PJM”) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. b. Third Party Provider Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to a Regional Transmission Organization (“RTO”) or an independent system operator (“ISO”), i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider’s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. Section 2: Applicability This Tariff is applicable to all wholesale power sales, including energy, capacity, and ancillary services, that are not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule of Seller. Section 3: Rates, Terms and Conditions All sales made under this Tariff shall be at rates, terms, and conditions established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. Section 4: Duration This Tariff shall continue in effect until terminated or changed and such termination or change becomes effective in accordance with any applicable regulatory requirements. Section 5: Modifications Seller may unilaterally apply, under Federal Power Act Section 205 and the regulations promulgated thereunder, to the Commission or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction for a modification of this Tariff. Section 6: Effective Date This Tariff is effective upon the date authorized by the Commission. Section 7: Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority a. Mitigated Markets Seller does not have authority under this tariff to make sales within the Nevada Power Company, PacifiCorp-East, or PacifiCorp-West balancing authority areas. See Sierra Pacific Power Co., 95 FERC 61,193, at 61,675, reh'g dismissed, 96 FERC 61,050 (2001); see also Sierra Pacific Power Co., 111 FERC 61,259, at P 21 (2005); Nevada Power Co., et al., 155 FERC 61,249 at P 3 (2016); Nev. Power Co., 189 FERC ¶ 61,225 (2024); AlbertaEx, L.P., et al., Docket Nos. ER25-335-000, et al. (Dec. 31, 2024). b. Mitigated Sales Sales of energy and capacity are permissible under this tariff in all balancing authority areas where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority. Sales of energy and capacity under this tariff are also permissible at the metered boundary between the Seller's mitigated balancing authority area and a balancing authority area where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority provided: (i) legal title of the power sold transfers at the metered boundary of the balancing authority area where the Seller has market-based rate authority; and (ii) if the Seller sells at the metered boundary of a mitigated balancing authority area at market-based rates, then neither it nor its affiliates can sell into that mitigated balancing authority area from the outside. Seller must retain, for a period of five years from the date of the sale, all data and information related to the sale that demonstrates compliance with items (i) and (ii) above. c. Exemptions Seller has the following authorizations and waivers of various Commission regulations: (1) Parts 41, 101 and 141, except for Section 141.15; (2) waiver of the reporting requirements of Subparts B and C of Part 35, except sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; (3) blanket authorization under Part 34 for all future issuances of securities and assumptions of liability. See Geysers Power Co., LLC et al., 87 FERC 61,108 (1999). Section 8: Compliance with Commission Regulations Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller’s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff. Section 9: Seller Category Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Northeast region, and a Category 1 seller in the Central, Northwest, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool regions, as defined in 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a).

MIDAMERICAN ENERGY COMPANY
And
CORDOVA ENERGY COMPANY
MISO PRA CAPACITY PURCHASE AGREEMENT
August 4, 2025
Tariff Submitter: MidAmerican Energy Company
FERC Tariff Program Name: Electric TCS and MBR
Tariff Title: MidAmerican Energy Company –Electric Tariffs
Tariff Record Title: MISO PRA Capacity Purchase Agreement
Record Content Description: MEC_Cordova
Tariff Record Proposed Effective Date: November 2, 2025
Option Code: A1
MISO PRA CAPACITY PURCHASE AGREEMENT
This Capacity Purchase Agreement (“Agreement”) is entered into this 4th day of August, 2025,
(“Effective Date”) by and between MidAmerican Energy Company (“Buyer”), an Iowa
corporation, and Cordova Energy Company, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Seller”).
RECITALS
1. Seller has agreed to sell all ZRCs registered from the Cordova Energy Center (as described
in Appendix A, “Plant”) for the MISO Planning Year 2027/2028; and,
2. Buyer wishes to purchase from the Seller all ZRCs generated by the Plant during such period
and to achieve and maintain accreditation of those Capacity Credits by MISO and other
entities and agencies to which Buyer may be obligated by contract or otherwise; and,
3. Buyer and Seller have agreed that the Seller will act as the MISO Market Participant for the
registration of the Plant as a MISO Planning Resource; and,
4. Buyer has agreed to make available to Seller, subject to certain reimbursements as described
in this Agreement, the amount of MISO Point-to-Point Transmission Service held by Buyer
necessary to effectuate pseudo-tying the Plant into MISO to support this Agreement; and,
5. Buyer is a rate-regulated electric utility and is engaged in the supply of electricity to the
public; and,
6. Buyer and Seller are FERC affiliates under section 205 of the Federal Power Act; “affiliated
interests”as defined in section 7-101 of the Illinois Public Utilities Act; and “affiliates”as
defined in chapter 476 of the Iowa Code.
NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of these premises, the mutual promises set forth herein and
other good and valuable consideration, Seller and Buyer agree as follows:
ARTICLE I
DEFINITIONS
For purposes of this Agreement, the following definitions shall apply unless the context otherwise
requires. All capitalized terms used in this Agreement that are not defined in this Article I shall
have the definitions contained elsewhere herein, including the Schedules hereto, or if not otherwise
defined in this Agreement, then in the MISO OATT or PJM OATT, as context requires.
1.1 Agreement: This Agreement, including all appendices, for the sale and purchase of
Capacity between Seller and Buyer as may be amended by the Parties from time to time in
accordance with this Agreement.
1.2 Auction Clearing Price (“ACP”): The price, expressed in $/MW-day, associated with the2
MW quantity that clears in the MISO Planning Resource Auction for a given LRZ or ERZ
for a Season for the applicable Planning Year.
1.3 Business Day: Any day except a Saturday, Sunday, or a Federal Reserve Bank holiday. A
Business Day shall open at 8:00 a.m. and close at 5:00 p.m. local time for the relevant
Party’s principal place of business. The relevant Party, in each instance unless otherwise
specified, shall be the Party from whom the notice, payment or delivery is being sent and
by whom the notice or payment or delivery is to be received.
1.4 Buyer: MidAmerican Energy Company and its successors and permitted assignees.
1.5 Buyer’s Requirements of Law: Collectively, the organizational or governing documents
of Buyer and any United States federal or state law, treaty, franchise, rule, regulation, order,
writ, judgment, injunction, decree, award or determination of any court or other
Governmental Authority, in each case applicable to or binding upon Buyer or any of its
property or to which Buyer or any of its respective properties are subject.
1.6 Capacity: The output potential a machine or system can produce or carry under specified
conditions. The capacity of generating equipment is generally expressed in kilowatts (kW)
or megawatts (MW). In terms of transmission lines, capacity refers to the maximum power
flow a line is capable of carrying under specified conditions. Capacity is also referred to as
“capability”in the electric power industry and, for the purposes of this Agreement, the
terms are synonymous.
1.7 Contract Quantity: The ZRCs of the Plant that are accredited by MISO for the applicable
MISO Planning Year.
1.8 Energy: An amount of electricity that is bid or offered, produced, purchased, consumed,
sold, injected, withdrawn, or transmitted over a period of time and measured or calculated
in megawatt hours (MWh).
1.9 Load: A term that refers to either an end-user of Energy, net of system losses, or the amount
of Energy (MWh) consumed by such end-user.
1.10 Load Serving Entity (LSE): Any entity that has undertaken an obligation to serve Load
for end-use customers by statute, franchise, regulatory requirement or contract for Load
located within or attached to the Transmission System, including but not limited to
purchase-selling entities and retail power marketers with the obligation to serve Load.
Where a distribution cooperative or a municipal distribution system otherwise covered by
the prior sentence is a wholesale customer of a generation and transmission cooperative or
a municipal Joint Action Agency, the generation and transmission cooperative, a state or
federal agency or municipal Joint Action Agency may act as the Load Serving Entity for
such distribution cooperative or municipal distribution system. Where retail Load
switching occurs in a state, the entity with the obligation to serve Load is the LSE.
1.11 FERC: Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and its successor organization, if any.
1.12 Governmental Authority: Any nation or government, any state or other political3
subdivision thereof, whether foreign or domestic, including, without limitation, any
municipality, township and county, and any entity exercising executive, legislative,
judicial, regulatory or administrative functions of or pertaining to government, including,
without limitation, any corporation or other entity owned or controlled by any of the
foregoing, in each case that has jurisdiction over any of the Parties or this Agreement.
1.13 MISO: Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. and its successor organization, if
any.
1.14 MISO External Resource: A generator located outside of the metered boundaries of the
MISO Balancing Authority Area.
1.15 MISO External Resource Zone (“ERZ”): A grouping of one or more MISO External
Resources in the same external balancing authority for purposes of the MISO PRA.
1.15.1 MISO Interconnection Agreement: The Generator Interconnection Agreement between
Cordova Energy Company LLC, MidAmerican Energy Company, LLC and Midcontinent
Independent System Operator, Inc. dated June 13, 2023.
1.16 MISO Local Resource Zone (“LRZ”): A geographic area within MISO that is prescribed
by the MISO, based upon the criteria in the MISO OATT, to address congestion that limits
Planning Resource deliverability.
1.17 MISO Market Participant: An entity that (i) has successfully completed the registration
process MISO and is qualified by MISO as a Market Participant, (ii) is financially
responsible to MISO for all of its Market Activities and obligations, and (iii) has
demonstrated the capability to participate in its relevant Market Activities.
1.18 MISO OATT: The MISO Open Access Transmission, Energy and Operating Reserve
Markets Tariff, including, but not limited to, the resource adequacy requirements of Module
E, and Business Practices Manual 011, as amended from time to time.
1.19 MISO Planning Reserve Margin Requirement (PRMR”): The amount of ZRCs required
of each LSE with Coincident Peak Demand in an LRZ to meet the LSE’s Resource
Adequacy Requirements in each Season.
1.20 MISO Planning Resource: A Capacity Resource, Demand Response Resource –Type I,
Energy Efficiency Resource, Load Modifying Resource, or Non-Emergency BTMG that
can be used to satisfy the MISO PRMR.
1.21 MISO Planning Resource Auction (“MISO PRA”): Auctions conducted by MISO to
determine the MISO ACP and the cleared ZRC offers for each MISO Local Resource Zone
and MISO External Resource Zone for each Season in the applicable MISO Planning Year.
1.22 MISO Planning Year: A “Planning Year”as such term is defined in the MISO Tariff
(currently June 1 of a calendar year through May 31 of the following calendar year).4
1.23 MISO Season: The four (4) seasons are (i) Winter –December, January, February; (ii)
Spring –March, April, May; (iii) Summer –June, July, August; and (iv) Fall –September,
October, November
1.24 MISO Zonal Resource Credits (“ZRCs”): Such term as defined and referred to in (i)
the MISO OATT or, in the event that MISO materially changes its market design from the
capacity construct after the Effective Date , then the Capacity shall be equivalent to a MW
from a Planning Resource that has been converted from a MW of Unforced Capacity to a
credit in the Module E-1 capacity tracking system or its successor (“New Credits”) (ZRCs
and New Credits shall be referred to herein interchangeably as “Capacity Credits”).
1.25 NERC: North American Electric Reliability Corporation or any successor organization
thereto.
1.26 Parties: Buyer and Seller, and their respective successors and permitted assignees.
1.27 Party: Buyer or Seller, and their respective successors and permitted assignees.
1.28 Person: An individual, partnership, corporation (including a business trust), limited
liability company, joint stock company, trust, unincorporated association, joint venture,
Governmental Authority or other entity.
1.29 PJM OATT: The PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff, including all attachments.
1.30 Plant: The generation and transmission facilities to the Point of Receipt built for the
generation of Energy and delivery of such Energy to the Point of Receipt. The Plant is
described in the Recitals and Exhibit A, owned by Seller and located on the Site.
1.31 Point of Receipt: The Point of Receipt is the Point of Interconnection as that term is defined
in the MISO Interconnection Agreement.
1.32 Regional Reliability Council(s) (“RRC(s)”): Any of the applicable NERC Regional
Reliability Councils or any other RRC which Buyer chooses to join, and any successor
organization(s).
1.33 Seller’s Requirements of Law: Collectively, the organizational or governing documents
of Seller and any United States federal or state law, treaty, franchise, rule, regulation, order,
writ, judgment, injunction, decree, award or determination of any court or other
Governmental Authority, in each case applicable to or binding upon Seller or any of its
property or to which Seller or any of its respective properties are subject.
1.34 Seller: Cordova Energy Company, LLC and its successors or permitted assignees.
1.35 Site: The real property on which the Plant and associated Interconnection Facilities are
located, including any related easements. The legal description of the Site is set forth in
Appendix A.5
1.36 Term: The period of time during which this Agreement is in effect.
1.37 Transfer Deadline: The date by which FRAPs must be submitted to MISO for the
applicable Planning Year.
1.38 Unavailable or Unavailability: A physical state in which the Plant is not capable of
delivering Energy, or in which any other equipment or facility is not physically capable of
performing its intended purpose.
ARTICLE II
SALE AND PURCHASE
2.1 Conditions Precedent
Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, this Agreement is contingent
upon:
a) Approval of the transactions provided for in this Agreement by the relevant
Governmental Authority(ies) with jurisdiction over the Parties or this transaction, and;
b) Receipt of a waiver of Seller’s capacity must-offer obligations under the PJM OATT
for the applicable delivery year.
2.2 Term
This Agreement shall be effective upon the Effective Date, subject to the conditions
precedent in Section 2.1 being satisfied, and shall apply only to MISO Planning Year
2027/2028. This Agreement shall expire upon the earliest of (i) an order from a
Governmental Authority rejecting this Agreement, (ii) mutual agreement of the Parties
terminating this Agreement and (iii) a Party’s delivery of a Notice of its election to
terminate following an Event of Default and (iv) fulfillment of the Parties obligations.
2.3 Sale and Purchase
Seller agrees to sell and the Buyer agrees to buy the Contract Quantity during the Term
subject to the terms of this Agreement. Buyer agrees to pay the capacity price for the
Contract Quantity for each MISO Season as follows:
Summer 2027: The MISO PRA ACP for Summer 2027
Fall 2027: The MISO PRA ACP for Fall 2027
Winter 2027/2028: The MISO PRA ACP for Winter 2027/2028
Spring 2028: The MISO PRA ACP for Spring 2028
2.8 Delivery and Receipt of ZRCs6
Seller shall electronically deliver the Contract Quantity to Buyer by submitting the
appropriate transaction(s) in the Module E Capacity Tracking (“MECT”) tool.
Buyer shall accomplish receipt of the Contract Quantity by confirming the appropriate
transaction(s) submitted by Seller in the MECT.
Seller and the Buyer shall accomplish delivery and receipt of the Contract Quantity no
later than five (5) Business Days prior to the Transfer Deadline.
ARTICLE III
PAYMENTS
3.1 Payment for ZRCs
Seller shall deliver to Buyer an invoice setting forth the amount due for a Season, calculated
as set forth in this Agreement, within five (5) Business Days after the results of the MISO
PRA have been posted by MISO for each Season. Within ten (10) Business Days of receipt
of such, Buyer shall pay to Seller the amount due as set forth in such invoice. To the extent
Buyer disputes the amount of the calculation, Buyer shall pay the undisputed amount within
such ten (10) Business Day period and shall in that same period deliver a written
explanation as to the basis for the dispute. The Parties shall promptly resolve the disputed
amount, provided, if they are unable to resolve the dispute within 15 Days, either Party may
initiate formal dispute resolution under Article VIII.
3.2 Reimbursement for MISO Transmission Service-Related Charges
Seller shall be responsible for reimbursing Buyer for any variable MISO or PJM charges
Buyer incurs related to Seller’s usage of Point-to-Point Transmission Service held by Buyer
required for Seller to implement and utilize the pseudo-tie to deliver Energy subject to the
provisions of Article 5.2. Buyer shall deliver to Seller an invoice setting forth the amount
due for a month, within five (5) Business Days of receiving an invoice from MISO for such
charges. At that same time Buyer shall deliver to seller documentation of the MISO invoice.
Within ten (10) Business Days of receipt of such, Seller shall pay to Buyer the amount due
as set forth in such invoice. To the extent Seller disputes the invoice, Seller shall pay the
undisputed amount within such ten (10) Business Day period and shall in that same period
deliver a written explanation as to the basis for the dispute. The Parties shall promptly
resolve the disputed amount, provided, if they are unable to resolve the dispute within 15
Days, either Party may initiate formal dispute resolution under Article VIII.
ARTICLE IV
SELLER’S OBLIGATIONS
During the Term of this Agreement, Seller hereby agrees to be bound by and to perform the
following affirmative obligations:7
4.1 Procurement of ZRCs
Seller shall work with MISO using reasonable efforts to obtain all ZRCs from the Plant for
the Term. Seller will comply with the terms of the MISO OATT with respect to data
collection, operational testing and any other MISO OATT requirements relating to
documenting the capability of the Plant for the purposes of determining its Seasonal
Accredited Capacity.
4.2 Market Participation and Operations
Seller shall register as a MISO Market Participant and be responsible for complying with
MISO OATT obligations applicable to resources that provide capacity.
As of the Effective Date, Seller shall use commercially reasonable efforts to obtain any
required approvals from PJM and MISO. Seller shall initiate and manage the process of
pseudo-tying the Plant to the MISO balancing authority and will be responsible for the
associated costs including all incremental and variable MISO and PJM charges related to
Seller’s usage of Point-to-Point Transmission Service held by Buyer required to implement
and utilize the pseudo-tie subject to the provisions of Article 5.2.
Seller shall be responsible for all fuel, transportation and Plant operating costs associated
with complying with its obligations as a MISO Planning Resource under the MISO OATT
and this Agreement.
4.3 Seller’s Cooperation
Seller agrees to reasonably cooperate with Buyer in any application or proceeding relating
to approval of this Agreement before any Governmental Authority, including, but not
limited to, the provision of information in its possession, custody or control necessary to
complete such applications or to respond to requests from any relevant Governmental
Authority or other persons party to a proceeding regarding this Agreement or Buyer’s
purchase of the ZRCs.
ARTICLE V
BUYER’S OBLIGATIONS
5.1 Regulatory Approval
Following execution of this Agreement, Buyer shall use its best efforts to obtain any
required Governmental Authority approval of this Agreement , including FERC and
Illinois Commerce Commission affiliate transaction approvals.
5.2 Buyer’s Cooperation
Buyer agrees to reasonably cooperate with Seller in any application or proceeding related to
approval of Seller’s request for a waiver of Seller’s capacity must-offer obligations under
the PJM OATT, including, but not limited to, the provision of information in its possession,8
custody or control necessary to complete such applications or to respond to requests from
PJM, the PJM Independent Market Monitor or other persons party to a proceeding
regarding Seller’s request for such a waiver.
Buyer shall be solely responsible for providing the Point-to-Point Transmission Service
necessary to pseudo-tie the Plant to the MISO balancing authority. Buyer will also
reasonably cooperate with Seller and MISO to effectuate the pseudo-tie arrangement,
provided that Seller will reimburse Buyer for any third-party expenses incurred by Buyer
related to such cooperation.
ARTICLE VI
FORCE MAJEURE
6.1 Force Majeure
It is understood that at times unavoidable delays or interruptions in delivery or performance
result from causes which are beyond the control of the affected Party or its contractors or
subcontractors, which the affected Party is unable to avoid or overcome through the
exercise of commercially reasonable due diligence (“Force Majeure”). Examples, when
meeting the requirements in the foregoing sentence, may include, but are not limited to:
acts of providence, fires, floods, tornadoes, sabotage, unavoidable accidents, riots, strikes,
slowdowns, lockouts, acts of war or terrorism, a Force Majeure event on the Transmission
Provider’s System as defined in the MISO Interconnection Agreement to the extent it
causes Buyer or Seller to be physically incapable of meeting its obligations under this
Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, “Force Majeure”shall not include the
following conditions: (i) late delivery to a Party of machinery, equipment, materials or spare
parts, unless such late delivery itself is caused by an event of Force Majeure; (ii) a delay
in the performance of any contractor unless such delay is caused by an event of Force
Majeure; (iii) normal wear and tear or random flaws in materials or breakdowns in
equipment; (iv) inclement weather ordinarily experienced in the area of the Site; or (v)
changes in the market conditions, action by Governmental Authority or weather conditions
that affect the cost of a Party to operate its business.
6.2 Remedial Action
The performance of each Party under this Agreement may be subject to interruptions or
reductions due to a Force Majeure condition and a Party shall not be liable to the other Party
if such Party is prevented from performing its obligations hereunder due to a Force Majeure
condition. The Party rendered unable to fulfill an obligation by reason of a Force Majeure
condition shall in good faith take commercially reasonable actions necessary to remove or
remedy the cause(s) and mitigate such inability to perform. The nonperforming Party shall
be prompt and diligent in attempting to remove the cause of its failure to perform, and
nothing herein shall be construed as permitting that Party to continue to fail to perform after
the cause of the Force Majeure condition has been removed. However, the obligation to
take such action shall not be interpreted to require resolution of labor disputes by acceding9
to demands of the opposition when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the Party
having such difficulty. If such Force Majeure condition continues for twelve (12)
consecutive months without being remedied, either Party may terminate this Agreement
upon thirty (30) days prior written notice, provided that, in such event, neither Party shall
be liable to the other Party for any damages pursuant to Section 7.4(a).
6.3 Notice
In the event of any delay or nonperformance resulting from Force Majeure, the Party
suffering the Force Majeure condition shall, as soon as practicable, but no later than two
(2) Business Day after the commencement of the Force Majeure condition, notify the other
Party in writing of the nature, cause, date of commencement thereof and the anticipated
extent of any delay or interruption in performance.
ARTICLE VII
TERMINATION/DEFAULT/REMEDIES
7.1 Events of Default by Buyer
The following shall each constitute an Event of Default by Buyer:
(a) Buyer fails to timely make any undisputed payment when due and fails to cure such
default within five (5) days after written notification of the breach by Seller.
(b) Buyer breaches any other material obligation under this Agreement, and fails to cure
such breach within thirty (30) days after written notification of the breach by Seller.
7.2 Events of Default by Seller
The following shall each constitute an Event of Default by Seller:
(a) Seller fails to timely make any undisputed payment when due and fails to cure
such default within five (5) days after written notification of the breach by Buyer.
(b) The Plant is Unavailable to provide Energy for ninety (90) consecutive days or one
hundred (100) non-consecutive days after the satisfaction of the conditions
precedent in Section 2.1 during the Term for any reason other than a Force
Majeure condition.
(c) Seller breaches any material obligation under this Agreement, and fails to cure such
breach within thirty (30) days after written notification of the breach by Buyer.
7.3 Termination
(a) In the event the defaulting Party fails to cure the Event of Default within the period
for curative action under Sections 7.1 or 7.2, as applicable, or upon the occurrence of an
incurable Event of Default, the non-defaulting Party may terminate this Agreement by
notifying the defaulting Party in writing of the decision to terminate and the effective date10
of the termination, which shall not be less than ten (10) days from such written notification.
(b) Upon termination of this Agreement, Buyer shall have no future or further
obligation to purchase the Contract Quantity or to make any payment whatsoever under this
Agreement, except for payments or obligations arising or accruing prior to the effective
date of termination and Seller shall have no future or further obligation to deliver the
Contract Quantity to Buyer, except for obligations arising or accruing prior to the effective
date of termination. After the effective date of termination, this Agreement shall not be
construed to provide any residual value to either Party or any successor or any other Person,
for rights to, use of or benefits from the Plant or the Buyer System.
7.4 Damages
(a) Except as expressly limited by this Agreement, for all claims, causes of action and
damages, the Parties shall be entitled to the recovery only of actual direct damages.
(b) Except as otherwise specifically and, expressly provided in this Agreement, neither

ARTICLE VIII
DISPUTE RESOLUTION
8.1 Dispute11
An authorized representative of a Party may submit a claim, dispute or other controversy
arising out of, or relating to, this Agreement which an authorized representative of a Party
does not believe can be resolved by the Parties’authorized representatives (hereinafter

within ten (10) days (or such longer time as the Parties agree) after notice to each Party of

8.2 Jurisdiction, Venue, Waiver of Jury Trial
Each of the Parties hereby agrees that any legal proceedings shall be submitted to a federal
or state court of competent jurisdiction located in Polk County, Iowa. Each Party hereto

proceeding brought in such a court has been brought in an inconvenient forum and agrees

inconsistent with the foregoing waivers and consent. TO THE FULLEST EXTENT
PERMITTED BY LAW, EACH OF THE PARTIES HERETO HEREBY WAIVES ANY
RIGHT IT MAY HAVE TO A TRIAL BY JURY IN RESPECT OF LITIGATION
DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY ARISING OUT OF, UNDER, OR IN CONNECTION

CONNECTION HEREWITH. EACH PARTY FURTHER WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO
CONSOLIDATE ANY ACTION IN WHICH A JURY TRIAL HAS BEEN WAIVED
WITH ANY OTHER ACTION IN WHICH A JURY TRIAL CANNOT BE OR HAS NOT
BEEN WAIVED.

ARTICLE X
FERC STANDARD OF REVIEW, MOBILE SIERRA WAIVER
10.1 Absent the agreement of all Parties to the proposed change, the standard of review for
changes to any rate, charge, classification, term or condition of this Agreement, whether

11.1 Assignment
